post_text:
Welcome to FIT Academy Charter School!
FIT Academy is a free public charter school serving students in grades K-9!

FIT Academy believes children must have a healthy foundation in order to achieve academic excellence. Our mission is to prepare students by providing a balanced approach to the mental, physical, and emotional development of children.

We are currently accepting applications for enrollment and several classes are approaching our enrollment limits for 2018-19.
Enrollment is currently accepted on a first-come first-serve basis. Please visit our website for more information or to enroll today!

http://fitacademymn.org/

post_text:
Pandemic-Electronic Benefit Transfer-Food Support--Application Deadline extended!
Families may qualify for additional funds to purchase nutritious food. Families with children ages 5 to 18 who qualified for free or reduced-price school meals, but not SNAP or MFIP, are urged to apply at www.mn.p-ebt.org or contact the P-EBT hotline to find out more: 651-431-4050 or 800-657-3698. Deadline is July 31, 2020.

Families with children ages 5 to 18 who received SNAP or MFIP benefits on March 18, 2020, received Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) benefits on May 30, 2020. Benefits were issued automatically and SNAP and MFIP families did not need to apply for these benefits or take any additional steps.

The weekly challenge for May 11th to May 15th is the Creative Quarantine Challenge!

For this challenge, we ask students and families to show us how they are spending their stay at home and social distancing time safely. Are you doing something creative to stay busy?

Share it with us at Creative Quarantine Challenge by the end of the day Thursday, May 14th.

Check out what our FIT staff has been doing at their homes!

Mr. McBride working on his music, Mrs. Halama working on her Pilates, Ms. Salzman doing fitness videos with her kids, Mrs. Starkey working on home improvement, Ms. Hanson refining her cooking, and Ms. Solbrack snuggling with her puppy....

The weekly challenge for May 4th-8th is Kindness! Do something kind for someone in your life and make sure to submit at Kindness Challenge by the end of the day Thursday, May 7th. Not sure what to do? Check out our ideas list!

Kindness Challenge Ideas

1. Give a compliment

2. Make a card or craft for someone

3. Share what you have with someone else

4. Give a gift

5. Help someone complete a task or chore

6. Hold the door for someone

7. Donate time to a good cause

8. Smile at others

9. Create a nice surprise for someone

10. Let a family member choose an activity

11. Use only kind words all day

12. Support someone who needs it

13. Say “thank you” to someone you appreciate

post_text:
Student Meals
District 191 will provide Grab-and-Go meals at five locations, weekdays through at least Friday, March 27. Both curbside pickup and delivery locations are available to any child ages 1 to 18.

Children may receive 2 meals each day (1 breakfast and 1 lunch per child per day). Children must be physically present to receive meals. Those who are sick or experiencing symptoms should not pick up meals.

CURBSIDE PICKUP
Meals will be available for curbside pickup at two locations from 11 a.m. - 1 p.m.

Nicollet Middle School (Door #20 near front entrance), 400 E. 134th St., Burnsville, MN 55337
Eagle Ridge Middle School (by the pool entrance), 13955 Glendale Road, Savage, MN 55378
DELIVERY
Meals will be delivered to three locations between 11 a.m. and 12:30 p.m.

11:00 a.m. - Arbor Vista MHC, 14750 Burnsville Pkwy, Burnsville, MN 55306
11:30 a.m. - Rambush Estates MHC, 14709 Burnsville Pkwy, Burnsville, MN 55306
12:00 p.m. - Chancellor Manor Apts, 14250 Irving Ave S, Burnsville, MN 55306

December Teacher of the Month!

Mr. Johnson- he was willing to move down to 5th grade and teach all new preps this year- a new grade level always presents some challenges and he is determined to make all students feel welcome, at home, and successful in his classroom. His positive attitude and love for education carry him through tough times- he is a bit on an island not quite elementary and not quite middle school which can be very lonely yet he persists.

Give to the MAX – Deadline is November 14

Our FIT Academy staff would like to issue a challenge to parents for Give to the MAX day, November 14th! Our staff pledge have to 100% participation and CHALLENGE families to do the same! Last year, we raised $3000 with our Give to the Max effort. This year, our goal is to reach $5000. 2 staff members have also pledged to donate $500 each IF we raise $5000 by that date!



This year, our goal is to raise $5000 to support our curriculum development. As a charter school, we receive significantly less funding than traditional public schools. As a young school, we also need funds to grow our school. Our primary goal this year is to grow our curriculum and we are focusing on fundraising for this purpose. Please visit our site to donate!

https://www.givemn.org/organization/Fit-Academy

Sincerely,

Claud Allaire
Executive Director

post_text:
Student Council is Hosting our 3rd Annual Food Drive for Open Door a local food pantry that provides programs to connect those in need with fresh and nutritious options.

Start Date: Monday Nov. 11th
End Date: Monday Nov. 25th at 9am

How the Drive Works:
-Students bring in canned goods and they are worth 1 positive point for your class or homeroom

-Students can give boxed food to other classes (classes must accept them and keep them)- those boxed items count as a negative points

-Winning class gets a pizza party paid for by Student Council

Have fun promoting a great cause helping others!

post_text:
Students learn about using renewable energy from the sun for heating and cooking as they build and compare the performance of 3 solar cooker designs. They explore the concepts of reflection, absorption, conduction and convection. Then they make and eat a quick-cooking food - s'mores!

A special shout out to our parents who volunteered in the class today and/or donated supplies for this project.

7th grade Project Lead the Way (Design & Modeling) students received this challenge today:
Build the tallest possible freestanding structure that can also be held upside down without losing parts within 20 minutes
Students had a limited number of resources to use to build their structure.
Partners Liam and Moses built the tallest tower and will receive a prize in class on Friday. Congrats to all builder for their participation and enthusiasm!
